commit 0f1212867ae91f845ec1f6ec6fc59d950cb3b6a4
Author: Sam <sam@sksamuel.com>
Date:   Wed Jun 10 01:04:48 2026 -0500

    Replace disabled-by-default assert range checks in CMYKColor with explicit validation (#665)

    The CMYKColor(c, m, y, k, alpha) constructor validated its arguments with
    `assert`, which is disabled by default in production JVMs. Out-of-range
    component values would therefore slip through silently and produce wrong
    colours in toRGB().

    Replace the five asserts with explicit IllegalArgumentException checks via a
    requireInRange helper that names the offending component and value, matching
    the existing RGBColor.requireInRange pattern (commit 30ac7fe9). The
    constructor signature is unchanged.

    Co-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
---
 .../com/sksamuel/scrimage/color/CMYKColor.java     | 19 +++++++++++----
 .../sksamuel/scrimage/core/color/CMYKColorTest.kt  | 27 ++++++++++++++++++++++
 2 files changed, 41 insertions(+), 5 deletions(-)

diff --git a/scrimage-core/src/main/java/com/sksamuel/scrimage/color/CMYKColor.java b/scrimage-core/src/main/java/com/sksamuel/scrimage/color/CMYKColor.java
index c2b40b12..35df74d7 100644
--- a/scrimage-core/src/main/java/com/sksamuel/scrimage/color/CMYKColor.java
+++ b/scrimage-core/src/main/java/com/sksamuel/scrimage/color/CMYKColor.java
@@ -13,11 +13,14 @@ public class CMYKColor implements Color {
     }

     public CMYKColor(float c, float m, float y, float k, float alpha) {
-        assert (0 <= c && c <= 1f);
-        assert (0 <= m && m <= 1f);
-        assert (0 <= y && y <= 1f);
-        assert (0 <= k && k <= 1f);
-        assert (0 <= alpha && alpha <= 1f);
+        // Validate explicitly rather than with `assert`, which is disabled by
+        // default in production JVMs (so out-of-range values would slip through
+        // and produce wrong colours in toRGB()).
+        requireInRange("c", c);
+        requireInRange("m", m);
+        requireInRange("y", y);
+        requireInRange("k", k);
+        requireInRange("alpha", alpha);

         this.c = c;
         this.m = m;
@@ -26,6 +29,12 @@ public class CMYKColor implements Color {
         this.alpha = alpha;
     }

+    private static void requireInRange(String component, float value) {
+        if (value < 0 || value > 1f)
+            throw new IllegalArgumentException(
+                "CMYKColor " + component + " component must be in [0, 1] but was " + value);
+    }
+
     public CMYKColor toCMYK() {
         return this;
     }
diff --git a/scrimage-tests/src/test/kotlin/com/sksamuel/scrimage/core/color/CMYKColorTest.kt b/scrimage-tests/src/test/kotlin/com/sksamuel/scrimage/core/color/CMYKColorTest.kt
new file mode 100644
index 00000000..683e255d
--- /dev/null
+++ b/scrimage-tests/src/test/kotlin/com/sksamuel/scrimage/core/color/CMYKColorTest.kt
@@ -0,0 +1,27 @@
+package com.sksamuel.scrimage.core.color
+
+import com.sksamuel.scrimage.color.CMYKColor
+import io.kotest.assertions.throwables.shouldThrow
+import io.kotest.core.spec.style.StringSpec
+import io.kotest.matchers.shouldBe
+
+class CMYKColorTest : StringSpec({
+
+   "valid components in [0, 1] are accepted" {
+      val color = CMYKColor(0.0f, 0.5f, 1.0f, 0.25f, 0.75f)
+      color.c shouldBe 0.0f
+      color.m shouldBe 0.5f
+      color.y shouldBe 1.0f
+      color.k shouldBe 0.25f
+      color.alpha shouldBe 0.75f
+   }
+
+   "out-of-range components are rejected with IllegalArgumentException" {
+      shouldThrow<IllegalArgumentException> { CMYKColor(-0.1f, 0f, 0f, 0f, 1f) }
+      shouldThrow<IllegalArgumentException> { CMYKColor(1.1f, 0f, 0f, 0f, 1f) }
+      shouldThrow<IllegalArgumentException> { CMYKColor(0f, -0.1f, 0f, 0f, 1f) }
+      shouldThrow<IllegalArgumentException> { CMYKColor(0f, 0f, 1.1f, 0f, 1f) }
+      shouldThrow<IllegalArgumentException> { CMYKColor(0f, 0f, 0f, -0.1f, 1f) }
+      shouldThrow<IllegalArgumentException> { CMYKColor(0f, 0f, 0f, 0f, 1.1f) }
+   }
+})

commit 21e83dced76b3c3e153db4211868690063f14448
Author: Sam <sam@sksamuel.com>
Date:   Wed Jun 10 01:01:45 2026 -0500

    Avoid per-pixel scratch array allocations in BlendComposite (#693)

    BlendingContext.compose invokes Blender.blend once per pixel, and every
    blend implementation allocated a fresh int[4] result array per call. The
    four HSL-based blenders (COLOR, HUE, LUMINOSITY, SATURATION) additionally
    allocated two float[3] scratch arrays per pixel. For a typical composite
    over an image this meant millions of short-lived allocations in the hot
    loop.

    The Blender.blend signature now takes a caller-supplied result array,
    allocated once per compose() call, and the HSL scratch arrays are hoisted
    to instance fields on the anonymous Blender classes. This is thread-safe
    because Blender.getBlenderFor returns a fresh instance per BlendingContext
    and a CompositeContext is used single-threaded per rendering operation.

    Every blender writes all four result channels unconditionally, so reusing
    the arrays produces bit-identical output.

    Co-authored-by: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
