Author: Sam <sam@sksamuel.com>
Date:   Thu May 28 23:41:10 2026 -0500

    Resample in premultiplied-alpha space to stop colour bleed (#521)

    ResampleOp blends the colour channels with the filter weights without weighting
    by alpha. Where a transparent source pixel holds arbitrary (often black)
    colour, that colour leaks into nearby visible pixels, producing dark/bright
    halos along transparency edges after Lanczos3/BSpline/Bilinear/Bicubic scaling.

    scaleTo now resamples in premultiplied-alpha space (which is linear and
    therefore separable): premultiply colour by alpha, resample, then
    un-premultiply. This is done on plain ARGB ints at the ImmutableImage level
    rather than inside ResampleOp, so it is independent of that class's internal,
    type-dependent channel ordering.

    Fully opaque images take the original path unchanged (verified byte-identical
    output for Lanczos3 and Bicubic). For an image with a transparent black region
    adjacent to opaque red, a boundary pixel that previously came back as
    r=241 (red dragged toward black) is now r=255 with the same alpha — colour no
    longer bleeds from the transparent side.

    Note: output changes for images that actually contain transparency, so any
    golden-image baselines covering transparent scaling will need regenerating.

    Co-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
