    Weight colour by alpha in LinearSubpixelInterpolator (#522)

    * Weight colour by alpha in LinearSubpixelInterpolator

    The bilinear subpixel sampler accumulated R/G/B with the bilinear weights but
    without weighting by alpha, so a transparent neighbour (which may carry
    arbitrary RGB) bled its colour into the result — visible as colour fringing
    along transparency edges.

    Accumulate colour premultiplied by alpha and divide by the summed alpha-weight
    at the end (un-premultiply); alpha itself is interpolated as before. When the
    combined alpha is zero the result is fully clear.

    Fully opaque sampling is unchanged (verified byte-identical subpixel hash over
    a grid of fractional coordinates). For a white-opaque pixel blended 50/50 with
    a transparent-black neighbour, the result is now white with reduced alpha
    (a=191, rgb=255) instead of grey (a=191, rgb=191).

    Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>

    * Add LinearSubpixelInterpolator tests for alpha-weighted interpolation

    Pins the premultiplied-alpha behaviour: a fully transparent neighbour's
    arbitrary RGB must not bleed into the interpolated colour (only alpha is
    blended), and interpolating between fully transparent neighbours yields a
    fully transparent result.

