Author: Sam <sam@sksamuel.com>
Date:   Mon May 11 23:04:06 2026 -0500

    Compose JPEG-safe (alpha-free) image in a single Graphics2D pass (#389)

    * Compose JPEG-safe (alpha-free) image in a single Graphics2D pass

    When the source has an alpha channel JpegWriter previously chained
    removeTransparency(WHITE) + toNewBufferedImage(TYPE_INT_RGB), which
    allocates and walks the pixel buffer twice (a per-pixel SrcOver
    formula via replaceTransparencyInPlace, then a Graphics2D redraw to
    strip the channel). Replace with a single TYPE_INT_RGB target filled
    white and drawn over once via Graphics2D — AlphaComposite.SRC_OVER
    onto an opaque destination produces the same blended result the
    manual formula computed.

    * Add JPEG alpha-compositing-over-white regression test

    Pins the contract for the single-Graphics2D-pass alpha removal: pixels
    with alpha=0 should resolve to (white background) and semi-transparent
    pixels should resolve to standard SrcOver-over-white blends. A 16x16
    image is used so JPEG's 8x8 DCT quantization doesn't dominate the
    measured channel values; sampling from cell centres keeps the slack
    small (< 12 per channel even at 95% quality).

    Without this test, a future regression that, say, dropped the white
    fill and started compositing over an undefined background would still
    silently produce JPEG bytes.
