    Replace assert-based input validation in subpixelSubimage and AlphaMaskFilter (#466)

    Two more sites where input validation lived in `assert` statements
    that are disabled by default in production JVMs:

      - ImmutableImage.subpixelSubimage's four bounds asserts let
        out-of-range x/y/subWidth/subHeight through. The result was a
        bare ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException out of getRGB deep inside the
        apply loop with no context. Now throws IllegalArgumentException
        naming the requested region and the source dimensions.

      - AlphaMaskFilter constructor's channel range assert let
        channel < 0 or > 3 through. The apply()'s switch matches 1, 2, 3
        explicitly and falls back to default for the alpha channel — so
        a bad channel value silently produced wrong (alpha-channel) output.
        Now throws IllegalArgumentException with the channel index.

    Update the existing SubpixelSubimageBoundsTest cases that previously
    asserted AssertionError (which only fired because Gradle runs with
    -ea) to expect IllegalArgumentException with diagnostic content, and
    add new tests for the right-edge / bottom-edge boundary error cases.

    Add AlphaMaskFilterChannelRangeTest covering channel<0, channel>3,
    and the boundary values 0 and 3 still being accepted.

    Co-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.7 <noreply@anthropic.com>
