commit 05c0161c054a9b6e42f4d14235593d09a5086203
Author: Sam <sam@sksamuel.com>
Date:   Sat May 2 00:08:13 2026 -0500

    Bulk-int rewrite of OpacityFilter, GrayscaleFilter, BlackThresholdFilter (#404)

    * Bulk-int rewrite of OpacityFilter, GrayscaleFilter, BlackThresholdFilter

    All three filters routed through MutableImage.mapInPlace((Pixel) -> Color),
    which means even after the bulk get/setRGB scaffolding (#385), the
    mapper lambda was still allocating per pixel:

    - OpacityFilter:        new RGBColor(...).awt() per pixel
    - GrayscaleFilter:      new RGBColor(...).awt() per pixel
    - BlackThresholdFilter: RGBColor.fromARGBInt(...).awt() OR p.toColor().awt() per pixel

    Each one was producing one RGBColor and one java.awt.Color per pixel —
    ~32M short-lived objects on a 4kx4k image, with .getRGB() called on the
    Color afterwards just to extract the ARGB int that RGBColor already
    held internally.

    Replace each filter's body with a direct bulk getRGB → in-place int
    loop → bulk setRGB. No per-pixel object allocation, identical math,
    identical output. The unused com.sksamuel.scrimage.color.RGBColor
    import is dropped from each file.

    * Add pixel-level tests for the bulk-int filter rewrites

    Each filter now has tests that pin its arithmetic to the integer:

    - GrayscaleFilter: luma value for a known input plus a 4-pixel
      row-major ordering check (red→54, green→182, blue→18, white→255)
    - OpacityFilter (new test file): boundary cases for amount=0, 0.5, 1
      with explicit per-channel and alpha expectations
    - BlackThresholdFilter: per-pixel below/at-boundary/above behaviour
      with alpha preserved in every case (transparent black stays
      transparent, opaque pixels keep their alpha)

    The existing image-comparison tests still cover the larger end-to-end
    output. These targeted tests catch off-by-one drift that a fuzzy image
    diff might miss.
