commit 172a97852b8cab192049b1346d2b6d9458cf4549
Author: Sam <sam@sksamuel.com>
Date:   Fri May 1 22:00:18 2026 -0500

    Wrap Graphics2D dispose() calls in try/finally across core (#432)

    * Wrap Graphics2D dispose() calls in try/finally across core

    Five sites in scrimage-core obtained a Graphics or Graphics2D and
    called dispose() inline:

       AwtImage.clone(int)               (else branch — type conversion)
       AwtImage.toNewBufferedImage(int)  (else branch — type conversion)
       AwtImage.rotateByRadians
       MutableImage.overlayInPlace
       Canvas.drawInPlace
       Canvas.draw

    If the intervening drawImage / rotate / draw call threw, control
    jumped past dispose() and the Graphics2D context leaked. The native
    AWT resources behind it (font caches, render queue, etc.) would stay
    live until the parent BufferedImage was garbage-collected.

    For long-running services that occasionally hit malformed input the
    leak compounds. Wrap each Graphics2D usage in try/finally so dispose()
    always runs, regardless of how the body exits.

    Tests in CanvasDisposeOnThrowTest exercise the exception path 200x —
    without the fix this would steadily leak Graphics2D instances; with
    the fix it completes cleanly. Two smoke tests also verify the
    underlying exception is still propagated correctly.

    Companion to #431 which fixed the missing-dispose bugs in
    BorderFilter and CaptionFilter.

    * Also wrap composite Graphics2D dispose in try/finally

    AlphaComposite.apply and BlenderComposite.apply had the same
    dispose-without-try/finally pattern as the core methods covered earlier
    in this PR. composite.apply is invoked by ImmutableImage.composite for
    every image-blend operation, so the leak in this layer compounds with
    every blend that happens to throw.

    Same fix shape: wrap setComposite + drawImage in try, dispose in
    finally.
