commit eddf5db1b7aa2da500116af4959bc154f26b5422
Author: Sam <sam@sksamuel.com>
Date:   Fri May 1 21:59:29 2026 -0500

    Short-circuit AwtImage.exists/forAll/count(Predicate) (#397)

    * Short-circuit AwtImage.exists/forAll/count(Predicate) without full Pixel[] alloc

    The three predicate methods went through Arrays.stream(pixels()), which
    forces pixels() to materialise the entire Pixel[] up front before any
    predicate is evaluated. Stream.anyMatch/allMatch short-circuit on the
    stream consumption, but the array allocation has already happened — so
    exists() on a 4000x4000 image always allocates 16M Pixel objects even if
    the first pixel matches.

    Replace with a single bulk getRGB into an int[] and a manual loop that
    allocates Pixel objects lazily, one per predicate call. exists() and
    forAll() now genuinely short-circuit; count() avoids the Pixel[] +
    Stream pipeline overhead.

    * Add regression tests for the short-circuiting predicate methods

    Verifies both correctness and the short-circuit contract:
    - exists() stops calling the predicate after the first match
    - forAll() stops calling the predicate after the first non-match
    - count(Predicate) returns the correct total

    The call-count assertions guard against future changes that
    re-introduce a Stream-based pipeline (or anything else that would
    materialise the full Pixel[] before the predicate could exit).
