Author: Sam <sam@sksamuel.com>
Date:   Fri May 1 21:58:51 2026 -0500

    Add StreamingWebpWriter mirroring StreamingGifWriter (#447)

    Animated WebP equivalent of StreamingGifWriter — assemble an animated
    WebP one frame at a time without holding every frame in memory.

      StreamingWebpWriter writer = new StreamingWebpWriter()
         .withFrameDelay(Duration.ofMillis(100))
         .withInfiniteLoop(true);

      try (StreamingWebpWriter.WebpStream stream = writer.prepareStream(target)) {
         stream.writeFrame(frame0);
         stream.writeFrame(frame1, Duration.ofMillis(250));
         stream.writeFrame(frame2);
      }

    The contract mirrors StreamingGifWriter:

      - Builder-style with withFrameDelay / withInfiniteLoop / withLossless
        / withQ / withM.
      - prepareStream(File / Path / String / OutputStream) — same fan-in.
      - Returns a WebpStream extending AutoCloseable, with the same
        writeFrame(image) and writeFrame(image, Duration) overloads.
      - Encoding happens at close().

    img2webp is a one-shot CLI, so writeFrame buffers each frame to disk
    as a NoCompression PNG and the actual encode is invoked from close()
    with all frames + per-frame delays. Buffering on disk (rather than
    memory) keeps the working set bounded for long animations.

    Static field `HANDLER = new Img2WebpHandler()` triggers Img2WebpHandler's
    static init the moment StreamingWebpWriter is first referenced, so the
    bundled binary is unpacked and chmod'd up front rather than mid-pipeline
    inside a try-with-resources.

    Extend Img2WebpHandler.convert with a per-frame-delay overload
    `convert(List<Path>, int[] frameDelaysMs, Path, int loopCount, int q,
    int m, boolean lossless)`. The existing single-delay overload now
    delegates to the new one with a uniform delays array.

    Add StreamingWebpWriterTest with 10 cases covering: OutputStream and
    File destinations, default vs per-frame delay, infinite vs single play,
    lossy vs lossless, close-without-frames, write-after-close, close
    idempotency, and the q/m range validators.

    Co-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.7 <noreply@anthropic.com>
