    Fix webp handlers leaking temp files on partial creation failure (#438)

    Two distinct leak patterns across the webp byte[] convert paths:

    1) DWebpHandler.convert(byte[]):

          Path input = Files.createTempFile("input", "webp").toAbsolutePath();
          Files.write(input, bytes, StandardOpenOption.CREATE);  // <-- before try
          try {
             return convert(input);
          } finally {
             input.toFile().delete();
          }

       If Files.write threw (disk full, permissions, ...) the temp file
       was leaked because the cleanup is in the try's finally and we
       never entered the try. Move Files.write inside the try block.

    2) CWebpHandler.convert(byte[]) and Gif2WebpHandler.convert(byte[]):

          Path input = Files.createTempFile("input", "webp").toAbsolutePath();
          Path output = Files.createTempFile("to_webp", "webp").toAbsolutePath();  // <-- can throw here
          try {
             ...
          } finally {
             input.toFile().delete();
             output.toFile().delete();
          }

       If the second createTempFile threw (disk full between the two calls)
       the first temp file leaked. Restructure into nested try/finally so
       each temp file is cleaned up independently, in the right order.

    These are edge-case leaks but real — for callers running long-lived
    processes that exhaust the temp directory, every failed conversion
    left a stale file behind.
